So, when I was putting this together, I was

00:05:55.910 --> 00:06:04.170
thinking, "What -- you know, why did I want
to write a book on this?

00:06:04.170 --> 00:06:14.750
And what are the reasons?
And what did I want to get out of it?”

00:06:14.750 --> 00:06:28.490
And the first thing I was thinking was that,
you know, doing math really helps you develop

00:06:28.490 --> 00:06:39.210
critical thinking and reasoning skills.
But, that was also the most boring reason

00:06:39.210 --> 00:06:51.889
I could come up with.
Of course, that's the reason why you take

00:06:51.889 --> 00:07:07.440
math in high school, but, you know, it's also
not very exciting.

00:07:07.440 --> 00:07:20.430
But one of the more practical reasons for
doing it is, it provides a good idea culture.

00:07:20.430 --> 00:07:47.210
So anybody who's watched the news lately has
heard a lot about the health care debate.

00:07:47.210 --> 00:07:56.750
You hear a lot of things like "socialism"
and, you know, "killing your grandma" and

00:07:56.750 --> 00:08:05.960
things like that.
But, when you get down to it, the health care

00:08:05.960 --> 00:08:14.190
problem, and health care in general, is really
just a math problem.

00:08:14.190 --> 00:08:26.780
You have X number of people that are in the
United States.

00:08:26.780 --> 00:08:45.129
Some fraction of them are going to get sick
during the next six months.

00:08:45.129 --> 00:08:58.959
And it's going to cost an average amount to
pay for that sickness.

00:08:58.959 --> 00:09:11.110
So we just spread out the average.
By just averaging over all people, we just

00:09:11.110 --> 00:09:24.279
get a rough estimate of how much we're going
to have to pay for everybody.

00:09:24.279 --> 00:09:34.959
It's a very simple math problem.
It's not very complicated at all.

00:09:34.959 --> 00:09:51.600
So really, if we're going to solve things
like this, it's helpful to just be able to

00:09:51.600 --> 00:09:57.880
go through the math, and have a very informed
public opinion on things like this.

00:09:57.880 --> 00:10:07.010
So that's kind of a practical reason for doing
these kinds of problems.

00:10:07.010 --> 00:10:16.510
And then, the last one is really that it's
just kind of a fun game to play.

00:10:16.510 --> 00:10:28.339
And I'll give you an example of what I mean.
So I was at the original Spiderman movie.

00:10:28.339 --> 00:10:44.759
I was sitting there with a friend.
And Tobey Maguire is on screen.

00:10:44.759 --> 00:10:54.100
He's, "Shoot the web. Shoot the web. Shoot
the web.”

00:10:54.100 --> 00:11:08.639
And if you look at it, the web's like this
thick.

00:11:08.639 --> 00:11:15.500
And it's going, you know, 30 meters out from
him.

00:11:15.500 --> 00:11:36.260
And the friend sitting next to me was just
like, "How much does he have to eat to produce

00:11:36.260 --> 00:11:46.930
all that web?”
And nobody actually ever sits down and takes

00:11:46.930 --> 00:11:58.279
the time to calculate it, unless you're a
geek like me.

00:11:58.279 --> 00:12:07.720
But that's basically the types of things that
I do.

00:12:07.720 --> 00:12:19.050
It's akin to doing -- I imagine doing with
a Sudoku or a crossword puzzle for anybody

00:12:19.050 --> 00:12:31.290
else.
So, I want to talk a little bit about how

00:12:31.290 --> 00:12:37.240
exactly we go about calculating something
like this Spiderman problem.

00:12:37.240 --> 00:12:48.740
And one method that you could use to do that
is something called the "Fermian Approximation.”

00:12:48.740 --> 00:13:00.999
So Enrico Fermi, who was an Italian physicist
 -- and a little bit of trivia for you -- half

00:13:00.999 --> 00:13:07.050
of the particles in the universe were named
after him.

00:13:07.050 --> 00:13:20.939
Well, he popularized this method of computing
things to within an order of magnitude.

00:13:20.939 --> 00:13:27.060
The approximation varies with -- .
It's called Fermian approximations.

00:13:27.060 --> 00:13:37.829
And basically is, he would go up to his students
and say, "You.

00:13:37.829 --> 00:13:53.189
Tell me the number of piano tuners in Chicago.”
And of course, you know, I can tell by the

00:13:53.189 --> 00:14:05.269
blank stare on your face that you have no
idea how to do that.

00:14:05.269 --> 00:14:25.339
And that's basically what his students thought.
But what he showed was that through very simple

00:14:25.339 --> 00:14:35.809
approximations, you can actually calculate
this and just about anything else.

00:14:35.809 --> 00:14:46.929
Just by starting to look at, you know, using
very simple math to do these order of magnitude

00:14:46.929 --> 00:14:52.720
estimates.
So the first step in this process is to use

00:14:52.720 --> 00:15:08.980
what you know or look up what you don't know.
So I can start by saying, "Well, you know,

00:15:08.980 --> 00:15:26.230
I can't figure out offhand just how many -- I
don't know offhand just how many piano tuners

00:15:26.230 --> 00:15:34.160
are in Chicago.
But I know roughly five percent of my friends,

00:15:34.160 --> 00:15:37.879
you know, or like one out of 20 of my friends
owns a piano.

00:15:37.879 --> 00:15:45.709
If I go down my Facebook page I say, "Well,
this person's musical.

00:15:45.709 --> 00:15:52.429
This one's not. This one's not. This one's
not."

00:15:52.429 --> 00:16:05.690
And five percent seems like a reasonable number.
Now, you say, "Well, you know, you can be

00:16:05.690 --> 00:16:19.570
way off on that.”
You're true. I could be way off on that.

00:16:19.570 --> 00:16:35.940
But I know that it's less than 50 percent
of people, because that would just be like,

00:16:35.940 --> 00:16:47.519
half of my friends don't own a piano.
So it's definitely less than that.

00:16:47.519 --> 00:17:06.830
But I know it's also more than one out of
every 200 people, because I know quite a few

00:17:06.830 --> 00:17:20.040
people with pianos and it would be odd to
have that few pianos.

00:17:20.040 --> 00:17:36.090
So I know that that's somewhere in the bounds
of what you'd expect to be reasonable.

00:17:36.090 --> 00:17:48.480
And you basically go down the line.
You write down all the things you know.

00:17:48.480 --> 00:18:02.510
So the next thing is that, if you have a piano,
generally get it tuned about once a year.

00:18:02.510 --> 00:18:14.040
Now, if you're very neglectful, you might
get it tuned once every three years.

00:18:14.040 --> 00:18:34.590
But you're not going to get it tuned once
every 30 years.

00:18:34.590 --> 00:18:55.690
So we're in the bounds of what's reasonable.
You're also not going to get it tuned, you

00:18:55.690 --> 00:19:06.680
know, five times a year.
Because that would be very expensive, unless

00:19:06.680 --> 00:19:21.690
you're somebody who really plays it often.
Most people are just getting it tuned, you

00:19:21.690 --> 00:19:34.880
know, one or two times a year.
You go a little bit further.

00:19:34.880 --> 00:19:42.920
You say, "Maybe a piano tuner tunes two pianos
a day.”

00:19:42.920 --> 00:19:55.190
And it's helpful to know the number of people
in Chicago is about three million people.

00:19:55.190 --> 00:20:11.080
You could just look that up on Google, or
you could know that roughly the number of

00:20:11.080 --> 00:20:20.020
people in a big city is about a million people,
but Chicago is a pretty big city, so maybe

00:20:20.020 --> 00:21:06.260
it has a few million people in it.
So these are all

00:21:06.260 --> 00:21:22.380
the things that you want to start off with.
And the next thing you want to do is, just

00:21:22.380 --> 00:21:36.760
like you did in high school chemistry class,
you just want to cancel units.

00:21:36.760 --> 00:21:52.190
So if I wanted to calculate the number of
pianos, well, I know there's three million

00:21:52.190 --> 00:21:59.620
people in Chicago.
I know there's one piano for every 20 people.

00:21:59.620 --> 00:22:09.830
So I just cancel units in the same way that
I did canceling grams per mole or whatever

00:22:09.830 --> 00:22:15.980
you did in high school.
Yeah. It's the same exact thing.

00:22:15.980 --> 00:22:23.000
So two divided by two is one.
Three divided by three is one.

00:22:23.000 --> 00:22:38.120
And people divided by people is one.
And then you just do that excessively.

00:22:38.120 --> 00:22:53.230
So people will cancel with people, pianos
will cancel with pianos, years cancel with

00:22:53.230 --> 00:23:02.950
years, days cancel with days, tunings cancel
with tunings.

00:23:02.950 --> 00:23:08.740
And if you multiply all these numbers together,
at the end of the day, you calculate, you'll

00:23:08.740 --> 00:23:14.820
get about 200 piano tuners in Chicago.
So starting from absolutely nothing, you really

00:23:14.820 --> 00:23:18.030
can just build up and figure out a way to
come up with a reasonable answer.

00:23:18.030 --> 00:23:37.530
Now, you might ask, "Well, how do you know
that this is anything close to the actual

00:23:37.530 --> 00:23:54.680
number?”
Well, if you look in the Chicago Yellow Pages,

00:23:54.680 --> 00:24:06.570
there's about 40 listings for piano tuners.
So we're off by less than a factor of ten.

00:24:06.570 --> 00:24:10.390
And we're probably even a little bit better
than that, because not every tuner is going

00:24:10.390 --> 00:24:19.450
to pay for a listing.
And the ones that are listed might have several

00:24:19.450 --> 00:24:26.740
tuners in them.
So we're actually pretty close in this regard.

00:24:26.740 --> 00:25:05.170
So, next, I'm going to get into -- what I
hope will be -- some fun examples for you

00:25:05.170 --> 00:25:15.600
guys.
I'm going to start with a disclaimer that,

00:25:15.600 --> 00:25:26.470
I just want to say, These are all just estimates.
I'm making no claims about their factualness.

00:25:26.470 --> 00:25:30.180
So, please don't sue me if I'm getting anything
wrong.

00:25:30.180 --> 00:25:35.120
And we're going to start with this guy, which
I'm assuming most of you all know him.

00:25:35.120 --> 00:25:44.840
For those of you who don't know him, this
is the Stay Puft Marshmallow Man.

00:25:44.840 --> 00:25:52.960
I suppose you could call him the character
